            <h4 class = "subtitle"> 
                As she strides with anticipation into the unfamiliar, pristine pale gray office, she can not help but wonder of the possible success that might transpire with a new position in her profession. After the passing of various months, she discovers that her male counterparts’ incomes are significantly higher. This is an extremely frequent occurrence and because of this, women, especially those of minority groups face great inequalities regarding their occupations. This site is dedicated to bringing awareness to the struggles that women face in the field of STEM.
            </h4>  
        </div>
        <div class = "body-content">
            <div class = "history">
                <div class = "historysubtitle"> a brief history: </div>
                <img src = "https://www.pbs.org/newshour/extra/app/uploads/2016/03/womenscientists_LOC_NationalPhotoCompany-1024x783-e1520552901245.jpg" class = "historycenter">
                This lack of representation has been alive for a tremendously long time, predominantly in earlier decades. Females were not given many educational opportunities, restricting their access to information as well as technology. This was because of expected gender roles and stereotypes. Even women who would finish their education, would not be given the option of full-time employment.
            </div>
            <div class = "stats">
               <div class = "stats-subtitle">stats:</div>
                <img src = "https://alltogether.swe.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Pay-Gap-in-Engineering.png" class = "statscenter">
                <br> - The average STEM salary for women is 60,000 dollars, while for laes, it's 85,000 dollars.
                <br> - Women of African and Hispanic descent in STEM earn an average of 52, 000 dollars a year.
                <br> - A majority of the lower paying workforce or fields, is occupied by women. Some feature home health workers, nurses, and pediatricians. 
            </div>
            <div class = "gender-gap-factors"> 
                <div class = "gender-gap-subtitles"> gender gaps in stem: </div>
                <br> Stereotypes: STEM  skills are seen as less-feminine from ages as young as four years old. These skills are not typically developed or nurtured for women.
                <br> Male-Dominated: Since more males work in STEM, these fields target men and appeal to them more than they would do for women. Some of these workforces demonstrate characteristics of exclusion and inflexibility.
                <br> Decreasing Amount of Influence: Girls from a young age do not have enough role models to help inspire or provoke interest for different fields in STEM. Females of color, having an even more difficult time with this.
            </div>
            <div class = "famous-women">
                <img id="adaLovelace" src="https://pbs.twimg.com/media/FMEXFcjUcAIdlpj?format=jpg&name=large"/>
                <p id="ada-caption" style="opacity: 0.0; transition: 0.1s ease-in-out">  Ada Lovelace was an early computer scientist who created the first computer program. The algorithm for Charles Babbage’s analytical engine was constructed by her, which would  later output Bernoulli numbers. At the young age of thirty-six, she died of uterine cancer, but her works greatly aided the development of computer science.</p>

