                <p id="curie-caption" style="opacity: 0.0; transition: 0.1s ease-in-out">   Marie Curie was the first ever individual to receive the Nobel Prize twice; the first prize in 1903 for her work in physics, and the second in 1911 for her work in chemistry. Curie’s work primarily focused on radioactivity, as well as the discovery of several radioactive elements. Curium was named after Marie Curie after her death in 1944 in honor to her. </p>

