                <img id="Franklin" src="https://pbs.twimg.com/media/FMEXFgEVIAA7cPo?format=jpg&name=large"/>
                <p id="Franklin-caption" style="opacity: 0.0; transition: 0.1s ease-in-out">    Rosalind Franklin was an English chemist whose work was mainly about molecular structures. It eventually created the base of our knowledge of the fundamental workings of microscopic things such as  DNA, RNA, and viruses. Franklin used X-ray crystallography to observe the helix shape of DNA. She died early at the age of thirty-seven. James D. Watson and Francis took the credit for her findings after she had passed. </p>

